\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
So, first of all, can you say where and when were you born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 I was born in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lancashire{\*\xmlclose}, in 1939 \endash  two days before the War broke out, so I\rquote m just a pre-War baby!
\par 
\par [LAUGHTER]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 So let\rquote 
s now talk first about family influences, because what we want to look at is what shaped your intellectual interests in the long run.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
But I think family background is very interesting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
My family is working-class.  It was a bit
 complicated, because my father had worked, during the War, for de Havilland, that made aeroplanes, which had a big aircraft place near Bolton, and then after the War he was a sort of semi-skilled worker.  But after the War, my mother\rquote 
s brother-in-law, who ran a kind of newspaper business, tempted my father into doing this, which proved to be a disastrous mistake, so that didn\rquote 
t last very long. And my father was then left without what had been a secure job at de Havilland, and eventually returned as a labourer, which he did then for the rest of his days.  Shall I talk a bit more about my childhood?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes please, yes.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15228468 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 I was the middle of three.  I have an elder sister, and she entered the 11+ as one did routinely in those days, and she won a place in Bolton
\rquote s top school, which was Bolton School. It has two schools, a Boys\rquote  School and a Girls\rquote 
 School, and it was a Direct Grant school, and half the places therefore went to kids who got through the 11+. My sister, apparently, was one of the top scorers, and my parents had never thought of that \endash  both of them had left school at 12 or 13 
\endash  but my mother, in particular, was keen on education, so my sister went.  So then four years later, it came to me to do the 11+, and I too won a place at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bolton
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and went.  And then three years later, my brother took the 11+ and he also got a place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}!  So three of us ended up at this school!  Life was not easy for my parents because we were relatively poor, and we all had to be kept on to 16 
\endash  that was part of the commitment of going to this school, so you couldn\rquote t leave, which I would have done if I\rquote d gone somewhere else, earlier, to go to work.  But as it happened, when I was there, the School Certifica
te was coming to an end, and that meant as the new system came in \endash  \lquote O\rquote  Levels \endash  the age restriction was removed.  So I was put in an express stream, because you didn\rquote 
t have to wait till you were 16 to take the School Certificate, and, in fact, I took \lquote O\rquote  Levels at 14.  But because we\rquote 
d been accelerated, you had to choose between Arts and Sciences, and I chose to do German, which meant I had to drop some science.  But because I\rquote d taken the \lquote O\rquote  Levels at 14, I then moved into the sixth form much earlier, in 
fact a special form was created to allow us to fill this period in between.  And so I began \lquote A\rquote  Levels - in fact, I too}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15228468 k my \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels when I was 16.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 My assumption had been, and my parents\rquote  assumption was I would leave school at 16. But the Head of the Sc
hool called my parents in, and said, \'93Your son ought to go to university\'94. And my parents said, \'93Well, no one in our family\rquote s ever been to university\'94, and he said, \'93Well, I think your son should go to Cambridge\'94
.  And so my parents said, \'93Okay\'94.  And my m
other went out to work to make sure that I could go.  My sister had left at 16, but my mother realised that if I was going to go, that means my brother would almost certainly have to go afterwards!  So there was a huge commitment that the family had never
 prepared for.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13331801 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
And what jobs did your sister and brother go in for?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, my sister ended up in nursing.  My brother also went to university three years after I did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 And what did he become?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
He became - a misfit.  He dropped out of university, although I think he was brighter than I was.  He\rquote 
s a very very able guy.  He dropped out of university and became a croupier in a night club, and then had a whole series of odd jobs, and he never really settled.  Twice married, both marriages collapsed.  And he died several years ago.  Very sad.  I
\rquote m glad my parents didn\rquote t live to see him, because he was such a good guy and very talented.  My sister did very well in nursing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Do you think you learnt
 something from your brother\rquote s experience?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, not really.  I think my life was formed, being three years older, and I had then settled down, I think. I\rquote d enjoyed Cambridge and settled down in life.  No, I learnt nothing.  I learnt a lot, of course
, from my parents, about commitment and sacrifice, which they did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Had your mother not been working until this happened, then, with the Grammar School?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, no.  She began working to aid the family finances, because my father was earning very little relative to the people I was at school with. She was famous for taking jobs that didn\rquote 
t last very long, but she kept going - but sadly died just after I\rquote d left Cambridge.  I think she was just worn out, to be honest, as I look back.  My father lived for many years later.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
And would you say you were close to your parents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
I was closer to my mother, I think.  I think we all were.  My father was a very good man, absolutely willing to work hard for the family, he wanted the best for us, bu
t he was rather a taciturn sort of man.  My mother, I think she was the one who had aspirations for us.  She was a great reader in a way my father was not, and she\rquote d quite an interest in the arts, so she followed what we did with great passion.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes, that\rquote 
s very interesting.  Were there any other people in the family who were important to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, not really.  Of course, in those days, if you were a working-class family in the North of England, kinship structures mattered. Both my parents had 
brothers and sisters, so we saw quite a lot of the family.  But as I say, no one had been to university.  And, in fact, my brother and I were the only two of that whole generation, on both sides of the family, who got higher education.  It changed, of cou
rse, with the next generation.  But we were seen as kind of slightly odd, and particularly in my case, going to Cambridge was seen as a very posh thing to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
So was that a bit difficult for you, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 No.  No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 You weren\rquote 
t bothered by their attitude?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, no.  No, there was no resentment at all, there was something of a pride in it, and I had none of the - as I later read, Jackson and Marsden\rquote 
s work about the fate of working-class children.  I never experienced any of those kinds of tensions either at Bolton School where, of course, most of my friends were middle-class and professional, or at Cambridge.  Maybe I was insensitive to it, or maybe
 I was fortunate, but I didn\rquote t have those problems - except that I always had less money than most of my friends.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
What about grandparents?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
All our grandparents had died when we were very young.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
I see.  It might be easier to go through the schools in sequence so you can say something about them.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
So what was the first one called?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
The first school? It was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Grove{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Primary School
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which was a short distance from the little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}Coronation Street}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 {\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 two-up/two-down where I was first brought up.  But then we moved later, and I went to another primary school, a little Church of England Primary School in Morris Green \endash  another part of Bolton \endash  and it was from there that I mov
ed to Bolton School, which, of course, was the big change in my life. Although my sister was going to Bolton School, the Boys\rquote  School was different, and I\rquote d never been to a school like that. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Would you say that at the primary school there were any teachers who were important in encouraging you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, I can remember them very well.  One remembers Mrs. Campbell and Mrs. Brown, in the last two classes I was in.  They were, of course, old-fashioned primary school teachers that taught conventional
 literacy and numeracy in a way that became less fashionable in some later periods!  (LAUGHS)  I do remember them, and I remember Mrs. Brown, because she encouraged me to write and direct a play, which, as I look back, was probably a very surprising thing
.
  Maybe some of my early interest in writing was beginning to come to the fore, because I always read a lot as a boy, but I loved this idea of writing something, and writing a play, which she encouraged.  That was more difficult when I went to Bolton Scho
ol, because I was just one amongst a lot of very much more sophisticated young people.  But I do remember those primary influences well, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 So can you talk about 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Well, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 is a very good school.  It was in beautiful buildings. It was a very traditional boys\rquote  school, now independent, with teachers wearing gowns, and it was a school that was very rich on the sporting side and on the kind of extra-curricular side.  My 
brother and I were opposites - I had no interest in sport, but I loved to belong to all these societies, and my brother was the opposite.  There was lots to do.  I enjoyed doing all the extra-curricular stuff, except sport. But nothing really happened unt
il this accident of my being accelerated through to \lquote O\rquote 
 Level early, and then finding myself in the sixth form very early, at 15, and suddenly realised that French was my best subject, and that you could actually start to think in French, and you could read
 in French without translating, and suddenly a whole new linguistic and cultural world opened up.  The teachers were, by today\rquote 
s standards, I suppose, fairly old-fashioned, but they were immensely able people, very committed, with extremely high expectations, and I think that\rquote s maybe its impact on me - their high expectations of me \endash 
 and I began to realise I was actually enjoying it.  I\rquote d not particularly enjoyed school before.  I was always in the top set, but I think I was rather a lazy person, basically!  If I didn\rquote t like something, I didn\rquote 
t do it.  But by the sixth form, I was liking it, and I wanted to do it, and I was encouraged by these men with their high expectations of me.  And so by the time I went to Cambridge, it almost seemed a natural thing to
 do, which is odd because it was utterly alien to anything in my family history, but it had begun to seem a natural thing to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
So can you talk a bit more about some of the teachers that were important at the Bolton School? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes.  They\rquote 
re very vivid in my mind.  Perhaps the most influential was a French teacher, who always challenged me, and I would ask him for things.  He would say, \'93Write an essay on Rousseau\'94, and I\rquote d say, \'93
Okay, what books should I read about Rousseau?\'94  And he would say, \'93Just read some Rousseau and then tell me what you think\'94
.  And this was really very difficult, you know, for a 16-year old!  (LAUGHS)  But in many ways he was the most important teacher because he constantly forced me back on my own resources. In fa
ct, when I went to Cambridge, and I got a First in my first year, I wrote him a letter \endash  the only time I ever wrote to a teacher \endash  and said, \'93
I think this is your influence, because you were the teacher who made me think for myself, gave me some kind of intellectual independence\'94.  Now, none of the other teachers did, but they were very good in their ways.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 What was his name?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
His name was Kenneth Haig, and very sadly he died two or three years after that - though he was only in his forties \endash  of a strange disease, which devastated me. It\rquote s in my mind very vividly, because I actually then went to see him \endash 
 he lived not very far from where I lived \endash  and \'85 er \'85 when I arrived at the house, his wife took me in, and she said, \'93You\rquote ve come to see Ken\'94, and I said, \'93Yes\'94.  And she said, \'93You obviously don\rquote 
t know that he died\'94.  And I was devastated, because I wanted to keep in touch with this man who I thought had taught me more than anything else, and it was not about the content, it was about the capacity to learn and think for yourself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, given that you later shifted into social research, was there anyone at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} who was in touch with that field?
\par 
