 or psychology.  I was convinced I wanted to work in the social sciences, but there had been no influence - that I\rquote m aware of - from my childhood.  I just got more and more interested in the human condition, and I think that\rquote 
s what appealed to me in literature, but I decided I didn\rquote t want to read Modern Languages, and I didn\rquote 
t know enough about either of them to know which I should do, and when I looked closely at what they were in Cambridge, in the end I chose psychology because it was a biological science, it was part of the Natural Sc
iences Tripos in Cambridge, and I thought, \'93That\rquote s going to be an interesting challenge\'94.  And I went to see the Professor, called Oliver Zangwill, who was a neuro-scientist, and he said, \'93We\rquote ve never had a theologian come before
\'94, he said, \'93but because you got a First, we\rquote ll take the risk and take you on\'94.  So that\rquote s how I ended up in psychology.  I could almost as easily have gone to do anthropology.
