\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15429306 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 The Head was crucial.  He was a quite remarkable figure, who\rquote s much admired by the people of the School.  He\rquote 
d been appointed Head at an early stage, came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Bolton{\*\xmlclose} from, I think from Charter
house, if I remember.  He was absolutely passionate about working-class kids of the North doing well, but I was only to learn that later.  He was a very very strong {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} man.  He was a very tall man with beautiful silver hair, and a white handkerchief sticking out of his pocket, and he was very grand sort of man.  He would tell people - you were called into his study, and he\rquote 
d tell you where you were going to go.  He wouldn\rquote t say about university, he\rquote d say, \'93I think you should go to \'85\'94, which he said to me. Actually, I\rquote 
d have been better going to Oxford because I might well then have read Modern Languages there, rather than switching to theology, because in Cambridge you had to do French and German - I didn\rquote t want to do the German.  So it shows
 how accidents can change your life!  (LAUGHS)  But he was undoubtedly an influence.  When he retired, he went to live in Oxford, which was central to the country, and when I went to Oxford in 1979, I used to go and see him. I got to know him better, and 
h
is wife, who was a very striking woman as well, and I kept in touch with them until he died some years later.  But he was much loved and much admired by the students, I think particularly those with my kind of background. Because I think, without him, wit
hout the impact on the School, I suspect I\rquote d have ended up - I don\rquote t know, at 16, the things that we were toying with was whether I would become a journalist, or possibly work in libraries \endash 
 something kind of literary was kind of in the air, but he was having none of that!  (LAUGHS)  I was going to go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which I did!
