\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2183341 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Well, actually it was a row with my par}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2183341 
ents, because the School had a \lquote Closed Exhibition\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859  at Emmanuel, Cambridge, and he said, \'93You\rquote 
re going to go in for the Closed Scholarship\'94.  And then he said, \'93They\rquote d been refused the year before\'94 \endash  the person that the School had submitted was not given this Closed Scholarship \endash  so he said to my mother, he said, \'93
We\rquote re sending David because we think he\rquote ll be able to break the tradition and be worthy of this Closed Exhibition\'94.  And my mother said, \'93Are you saying to me, Mr. Poskitt, you\rquote re using my son as a kind of experiment?\'94
  And he said, \'93Well, yes, Mrs. Hargreaves, if you want to put it like that\'94.  And she said, \'93Oh no you\rquote re not, Mr. Poskitt\'94. Which amazed me, given the social gap between my mother and this man.  She said, \'93
Nobody is using my son as an experiment for anything\'94.  And she came home and told me, and I was completely aghast at this,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2183341  as you can imagine!  (LAUGHS)  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 So my mother very sensibly said, \'93Well, there must be other Colleges\'94, and she said, \'93I think he\rquote 
s right that you should go to Cambridge.  I\rquote m persuaded that you should, and your father is coming along with it\'94
.  So we got all the stuff out, which was much more complicated in those days, and we chose another College, and we went there, against Richard Poskitt\rquote s better judgement.  But when I got in, he was as delighted as anybody else, and it was fine.

