\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
So did he have much contact with you, in general, through your time at the School, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, no.  He taught us for religious education, but in the first year, he was passionate about - he had to know e
very boy as they joined the School, and he taught in the sixth form.  It was allegedly religious education, there was some kind of vague theological theme running through it, but it was really an excuse to talk to the boys and what we would nowadays call 
G
eneral Studies.  I mean, he simply wanted boys to talk.  And I think, for him, it was important to give young men confidence.  I think he was a great believer in people having to be confident in what they were doing.  And the kind of Societies I enjoyed, 
like the Literary and Debating Society, the School was very good at cultivating people who could make an argument and defend a position, and I think that was a striking influence.  So he, in his personal dealings with the boys \endash 
 although I was never close to him as a schoolboy, I mean, I don\rquote t think I was a kind of favourite or anything of that kind \endash 
 I was part of the process about what he had to do with boys to get them to a certain stage by the time they were 17 or 18.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Very interesting.  So in a way, for you, I suppose, he\rquote s a model of a successful teacher?  Or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, since I entered teaching later, it wasn\rquote t his method of teaching perhaps, so much as a commitment to wanting us to be articulate and independen
t, and also just civilised - I mean, he would talk about things that we may have known little about.  He\rquote d talk about politics, he\rquote 
d talk about culture, general cultural things.  So when I became a teacher, I think it did have an impact on me, that when I 
taught sixth formers I would expect them to have a working knowledge of key novels or key figures, key intellectual figures.  The school I taught at first was a grammar school, famous for having produced Wilberforce and Andrew Marvell, but it was a much l
ower key school than Bolton School, and it certainly didn\rquote t have this Oxbridge orientation that marked Bolton School. So I felt, when I went there, I had to carry some of that heritage I\rquote 
d picked up from my own schooling when I taught the sixth formers, and I think it did affect probably the style I did, because I was always challenging them, why hadn\rquote t they read such a thing?  And they\rquote d say, \'93We\rquote 
ve never heard of it\'94.  And I would say, \'93Well, you know, you\rquote re not really an educated person unless you\rquote ve read that\'94.  So it did have an impact, yes.
\par 
