\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Because you\rquote 
d already done this dissertation.  But can you explain \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, no, just part of the Tripos.  It was only a small project.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
What was it about, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
It was about testing people\rquote s interests.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Oh!  So how did you do that, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, it was based on some work a man called Brook had done before, with Alice Heim, and he\rquote d died, tragically, and so I was doing some work to move the work on, and it was quite interesting.  The question came up about research.  I didn\rquote 
t want to research in psychometrics.  The only thing that, really, I was at all interested in at that stage, was what later became known as autism \endash  it wasn\rquote 
t called that then, it was usually called childhood schizophrenia, or other kinds of names were given to it.  But I was intrigued by these communication and relational difficulties that some children had, which I\rquote 
d done as part of the abnormal psychology course.  But I decided, instead, I would go and teach for a while. I never really planned to end up in educatio
n.  I thought I must sort myself out - I was still sorting myself out, sexually, in terms of my identity, and I really wasn\rquote t sure what career I wanted.  So I thought, \'93I\rquote ll go and teach for a year or two, it\rquote 
s a safe enough thing to do\'94.  And that\rquote s when I went teaching.  And I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hull{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to teach.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Is that 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Hull{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Grammar School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} you went to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
It was Hull Grammar School. Which I enjoyed.  I thought it was great fun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But what did you teach?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 I taught
 Religious Education and English. In those days, of course, there was no National Curriculum, you just went in and people said, \'93Teach whatever you like\'94 \endash  it\rquote 
s bizarre, as I look back!  But I enjoyed the work very much, but it was clear I wasn\rquote t going to do it for very long.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Why was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, I remember one day, sitting in the Staff Room, and all the young members of staff sat at one end of this oblong room, and all the Heads of Department sat round the electric fire at the other end, with chairs that were unique to them \endash 
 you couldn\rquote t sit in their chairs, they had their own chairs.  And I remember, one day, looking up along the Staff Room, and thinking, \'93I can see a 40 year trajectory here as I progressively move up the Staff Room and end 
up with my bum on one of these chairs round the fire!\'94  And I thought, \'93This is not going to satisfy me!\'94  (LAUGHS)  So it was clear I was going to have to go back and do some kind of research. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Can you say a little bit more about this school experience, because, I mean, this is the only time, apart from the research, that you\rquote ve taught, isn\rquote t it.  Or am I wrong about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Taught as a paid teacher, yes.  I did teach later in the school I studied at, but,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1393686  yes, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 the only time I\rquote ve taught as a full-time teacher.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
I think it would be very interesting to hear more about your experience of being a full-time teacher.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, in those days it was very much sink or swim.  I was an untrained graduate, I could have done a PGC, but everyone told me it was a waste of time, so, of course, I didn\rquote 
t do it.  Why would I do something that was a waste of time?  So I just walked in, and the bizarre thing was, you were given a class - you were made the form teacher of a set of new boys, when you were co
mpletely new to the school!  So, of course, they asked me questions to which I didn\rquote t know the answers!  I didn\rquote 
t even know the geography of the wretched place!  But it was sink or swim. A group of people had come in when I did, several young teachers had 
come in, including several Oxbridge people, and it was sink or swim. You really had to decide you were going to be tough and not let them make a fool of you, or you\rquote 
d be made a fool of very quickly - which happened to one of us. I was fine, I decided to play it fairly tough, which worked, so that I didn\rquote 
t actually have any real trouble as a teacher, whereas this other chap - who I shared digs with for a period - did, and never recovered, really, from it, because kids can be very hard on you.  But I enjoyed teaching.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
So what kind of discipline did you use, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, you know, you just have to make it clear you\rquote re not going to be made a fool of, and if people call your bluff, they try to call your bluff, that\rquote s what kids do, and you don\rquote 
t let them get away with anything, and if you do that, you\rquote re fine.  The school also taught me to play bridge - at lunchtime!  (LAUGHS)  The school was interesting, because it had people who were very much Hull born and bred.  I didn\rquote t like 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Hull{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} at all, I thought it was a horrible place.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Why did you think it was horrible, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Because it was so parochial \endash  but this was before the Humber Bridge, not that I think that made a great deal of difference \endash  but there were too many old boys on the staff, for a start, so there was a kind of parochialism which I didn\rquote 
t like. And I thought, \'93This is not the place where I want to be\'94.  And there wasn\rquote t all that much going on in the town.  Although it was supposed to be a big city, I\rquote d have been m
uch more comfortable in a Manchester or a Leeds, not that I particularly wanted to be in the North, but I wanted a more lively place to be.  It was a bit dead.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Was it just a boys
\rquote  school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
How did you get them interested in religious studies?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 I\rquote 
m not sure that I did!  (LAUGHS)  Well, I had an \lquote O\rquote  Level group \endash  I told the Head I wanted to have a group to do an exam, because they wanted exams, and I said, \'93Well, they don\rquote t take it seriously if there\rquote s no exam
\'94
.  So that was all right, I got that going, and got them through.  And the sixth form, I treated it rather like Richard Poskitt had treated me. It was loosely religious, but it was really about - I suppose I built in a fair amount of social science one wa
y and another \endash  it was about the human condition and our relation to eternity and all that kind of stuff.  And, of course, sixth form students are intelligent and interested, and late adolescents, they\rquote re fun to talk with, and they\rquote 
re curious, and challenging, so teaching wasn\rquote t, in that sense - if you\rquote ve no discipline problems, teaching in a selective school isn\rquote t hard.  I mean, it isn\rquote t hard at all, if anything, it\rquote 
s insufficiently challenging because it\rquote s easy to do \endash  and I wanted more challenge in my life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Then you say you decided you\rquote d got to move on from this and do some research. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6708948 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Well, the story I\rquote ll now tell will be very interesting in the Archive, because it\rquote 
s days that are unthinkable any more!  There was a job advertised at Manchest
er, and I had possible reasons for returning there because in my first term in Hull, my mother died suddenly and tragically, and my father was on his own, and my brother was still in the middle of university, so there were some reasons why I might want to
 return to Lancashire.  And a job came up, advertised by W.J.M. McKenzie \endash  Bill McKenzie \endash  who was then the Professor of Government, in the Dover Street Group at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.  And I can\rquote t, to this day, remember what the advert was about, but it was a kind of intriguing thing, so I went to see him.  And we chatted a bit \endash  and this was for a Research Assistant\rquote s post 
\endash  and I said, \'93But what, exactly, would you want me to do?\'94  And he said, \'93Well, I don\rquote t know.  I don\rquote t know really\'94.  And I said, \'93Well, I really don\rquote t know anything about government\'94.  He said, \'93Don
\rquote t worry about that, you can pick it up in six months.  You know, you just have to do a bit of reading.  I mean to say, we\rquote ll }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1393686 
find something for you to do\'94.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 So anyway, he sat back and he said, \'93Well, actually, there\rquote 
s another job going in the building.  If you like, you could go and see Professor Chester\'94, who was the Professor of Social Administration, and [Mackenzie] said, \'93He\rquote s got a job going in the National Health Service\'94.  And he\rquote d asked
 about my family, and I\rquote d said my brother-in-law was a Hospital Administrator, and my sister was a Hospital Sister, and because we were poor, I\rquote d had to work throughout my vacations at Cambridge, and I\rquote 
d worked in the hospital.  So I said I knew quite a bit about hospitals, having spent a fair amount of time in them \endash  not about medicine, but about hospitals \endash  and he said, \'93Oh, go and talk to Chester about it\'94
.  So I went to see him, and he said, \'93Oh yes, yes\'94, he said, \'93you sound to be just the man for this job really\'94.  He said, \'93We\rquote re doing research into how hospitals run\'94.  I didn\rquote 
t know that, but he became an international authority o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6708948 n the National Health Service.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But then as we were chatting, he said, \'93Do you know,\'94 he said, \'93If you\rquote ve been in a school, there\rquote s a job going, upstairs, in Anthropology, studying schools\'94
.  He said, \'93Why don\rquote t you go up and see Max Gluckman?\'94  (LAUGHS)  So I went upstairs and saw Max Gluckman and some of his colleagues, who told me about the work they were doing in schools.
  And, of course, it was incredibly relevant to what I was doing, so I was offered three jobs as a Research Assistant!  And I decided, in the end, I would take the job studying schools, I don\rquote 
t know why.  I suppose I felt a little bit more secure because it was something that I knew something about \endash  schools \endash 
 and it was quite interesting to me how schools ran, even though of course, I had no anthropology at all!  But then I had no social admin and had no government!  So all these jobs were going to be a ch
allenge in a new way. So I took the job in the Anthropology Department.
