 them, actually.  I mean, school was awful for them.  They got the worst teachers.  It was boring.  There were no public exams.  There was nowhere to go.  They were poor, their prospects were not good.  They spent much of their life thieving, and generall
y being \'85 But, you see, they were actually - I took them once \endash  because they were much more talented at art than they alleged.  I once foolishly said to them, \'93Have you ever been to an art gallery?\'94  And they said, \'93No\'94
.  And I said, \'93Well, okay.  I\rquote ll take you to the Whitworth Art Gallery\'94. And there were some - what\rquote s the guy\rquote s name?  - they had a lot of pictures up where the oil was standing off the picture.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yeah.  Not Jackson Pollock?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
No, but it was that kind of stuff. I\rquote ve just forgotten his name, but it might come back to me.  And we went round looking at these, and it wasn\rquote 
t kind of Michelangelo fine drawing, these huge pictures that were 8 feet by 4 feet, with thick paint on them.  Well, these kids had never seen such a big picture, and they\rquote 
d never seen oil put on in that kind of way, and they were desperate to touch it, and there was this guide in the Art Gallery, running round after me, saying, you know, \'93You must stop your kids touching the pictures\'94, and, of course, their natural i
nstinct was to do this.  And although they were thieves they were fascinated by life, and you realised what terribly narrow lives you could lead in an enclave, at that time, in the central slums of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Salford
{\*\xmlclose}, that these kids hardly ever moved out of.  So
 I think I just tried to get to know them as people, and recognise that there was more to them than first met the eye, because I suppose I saw them in a more rounded way than I would have done if I\rquote d been an ordinary teacher there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 And given their k
ind of culture as a group, how did they relate to teachers normally?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, it depends.  The upper streams, of course, were \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
I mean the more difficult ones.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
The more difficult ones?  Well, they were very difficult with some of the staff, and they led them a merry - sometimes I had to actually come out of lessons because they were giving the teacher such a hard time \endash 
 it was embarrassing, for me, to see the teachers losing face in front of me, so I had to find an excuse to kind of slip out \endash  because they could be very difficult.  The Deputy Head was an iron disciplinarian, they\rquote 
d never behave badly for him, because he knew how to do it.  But some of the weaker teachers \endash  by definition, were those that had weaker discipline \endash  and they were given these kids}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4357405  to keep them out of mischief, \lquote Keep them occupied\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
, because the school basically said it wouldn\rquote t keep them from wrecking the place, and they don\rquote t actually run out of school, then fine.  But that was the way it was.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 You mentione
d with, I think, some of the less successful teachers, that they would go in for withdrawal.  What do you mean by that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
They stop seeing things they didn\rquote t want to see, because they couldn\rquote t control them, so it became a kind of selective perception, and it was disconcerting to witness, because you could see honourable men failing professionally, and it
\rquote s never pleasant to see people falling below standards that they would - because in the Staff Room, they present themselves as competent teachers, because that\rquote 
s what you have to do with your colleagues. So I was seeing a kind of double life that some teachers lead, which is where the Goffmanesque kind of stuff comes in, there\rquote s a presentation of self to colleagues, who couldn\rquote 
t see backstage. But there was I, in the classroom, and it became difficult.  I can\rquote t think, in the end, anybody who actually wouldn\rquote 
t ever have me in the classroom, but I had to be discreet, and sometimes coming out when I saw, as Goffman would say, \'93Their front was collapsing, visibly, in front of my very eyes\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Is the book, do you think, to some extent, a study of two conflicting cultures within the school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Do you mean the staff or students, or between the students?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Between the students I
\rquote m thinking of more.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Oh yes, I mean, there were two competing cultures. I\rquote d felt that was, to some degree, true in the grammar school where I\rquote d taught.  It wasn\rquote t probably as acute, but remember, there, I was a teacher, so I didn\rquote t see it as fully.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
But was the book novel in studies of schools, in having that kind of perspective?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Perhaps putting it quite so sharply, yes, but there were fictional accounts of Partridge, and Edward Blishen and things that had captured some of that.  I think perhaps putting it in the way I did.  I think it\rquote 
s the book people have talked most to me about in subsequent years, and, in fact, twice in the last two weeks, a Headteacher \endash  I did a lot of work with Heads still \endash  has mentioned the book to me, people I\rquote 
ve never met before. I think it\rquote s because at the time, a lot of people said, \'93This could be our school\'94
.  It had had some kind of ring of authenticity.  Now, whether it was the two cultures, or whether it was something about the way teachers behave and tal
k, and the way kids do things and so on to some degree, this differentiation amongst the kid - the polarisation into cultures - they come out more sharply than was true in the Parsons\rquote  study. Because the Parsons\rquote 
 study was a very cool, intellectual, analytic piece \endash  very low on a sense of what it feels like to be in the school.  And I think there weren\rquote 
t many things around, so it got adopted quickly as a course book for teacher training, because it was about a real school, and real kids were talking. Though
 it certainly was an extreme, I chose there because it was kind of extreme.  But people saw resonances, as I, myself, saw resonances right to the grammar school.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Isn\rquote 
t there a bit of a paradox when you say, \'93The primary function of the social researcher is to make a diagnosis, not prescribe a cure\'94, and yet, in a way, you produce a book which was used for teacher training?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yeah, because there was a lot of stuff around then, about \endash  and the book was used for this \endash  either against streaming, or
 against the secondary modern system, and I was anxious, rightly or wrongly, not to get too caught up in that world.  I was pressed by people in subsequent years, to join a bandwagon for the comprehensive and against the sec. mods., on the basis of this w
ork. I remember writing that, I remember thinking my job, first of all, was what later wo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15824994 uld be called by ethnographers \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 the appre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15824994 ciative stance\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 .  I think my job there was to understand and be faithful to what I was seeing.  In that sense, I was perhaps be
ing quite a good anthropologist, was I?  Yes!  Rather than an educationist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 It seems like it
\rquote s the correct anthropological position, but doesn\rquote t fit with what you later go on to do, which is to tell people how to change things!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15824994 (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 No, because that\rquote 
s why I said the book changed my life. I think one of the great difficulties of doing ethnography early in your career, and perhaps as we talk further I\rquote d want to argue some of the things I learned, and some of my ways of looking at 
the world and at life, that started with that study in Lumley, are with me to this day.  To this day.  I mean, it\rquote s imprinted itself on me.  It\rquote s a stamp for life.  Now, whether that\rquote s true of most people\rquote 
s work for their first kind of major piece, I don\rquote t know, but it\rquote s certainly true of mine.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Which aspects, in particular, are stamped on you for life?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15824994 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
An obsession with people, not systems, even when I talk about systems.  A concern with authenticity and evidence.  A concern always to relate what you say somehow back to people and their lives. But it partly changed, because if you move into education - 
no, I want to say two things.  One, when you take a full-time job as a lecturer, you can\rquote t go on being an ethnographer, because although I\rquote ve done bits of ethnography and I still will talk about that, still when I\rquote 
ve been given a chance, I\rquote ve gone back and done ethnographic type work, even in very different settings, like hospitals which I did a little bit later, I wrote two books about.  And it\rquote 
s a tragedy in a way, because anthropologists build it in.  They have to go off and do fieldwork, don\rquote t they, they always have great chunks when they go off and do it, but I couldn\rquote t, working in an Education Faculty, say, \'93
I need a year to go off and do anthropological work\'94.  You can\rquote t do it.  And I suspect most anthropologists don\rquote t go on doing it.  So that was the first change in my life \endash  I knew I couldn\rquote t go on doi}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15824994 ng endless Lumleys as it were.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
But the second was, I was now in a field where I was talking about how the world should be, because that\rquote s what education is about.  Education has to have a strong prescri
ptive element, and so I was pushed into a world where I was having to say, not just \'93This is the way the world is\'94, but \'93This is the way the world perhaps could and should be\'94. I suppose I\rquote 
ve had to live with that tension, in a way that if I\rquote d not been in an applied Department \endash  as education is always an applied social science \endash  if I\rquote 
d stayed in mainstream sociology or anthropology I probably would have looked at it differently.  I\rquote d have ended up with some of the people I\rquote ve exchanged views with and have admired as friends, people like Martyn Hammersley, he\rquote 
s in an Educational Faculty, Martyn was in Dover Street at the same time I was, but he\rquote s been able to stay much more kind of purely as a social scientist.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13331801 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
