s very interesting.  The last thing about that book was the various people you mentioned, and I\rquote m just wondering whether I could run through their names to see whether you want to make any comments.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 There\rquote 
s Audrey Lambert.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yeah.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
She was one of the co-researchers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 She\rquote 
s one of the three.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid16450274 
At the time it was very tense, because the relationships between Audrey and Colin were poor, and then subsequently my relations with Colin were very poor.  Neither of us found him very easy to get on with.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
  Audrey and I got on quite well.  Her problem - she was married, and she adopted a child in the middle of all this, and then as sometimes happens with older women who adopt, they instantly become pregnant, which she did (LAUGHS) and so sh
e suddenly had two kids. And she was finding her work - she was, of course, much more the trained anthropologist, but she found it difficult to make headway with a good story about her school. I think that\rquote 
s the luck of the draw.  I think, as a social scientist, you can be lucky or unlucky where you choose to do your fieldwork, or what your first project is. She used to come with all this complicated material and show it to me, and say, \'93
Can you make much out of this?\'94  Well, I couldn\rquote t make head nor [tail], there seemed to be no patterns, it was difficult to see what it was all about, and I don\rquote 
t think she ever really published very much.  I rather lost touch with her. But I probably saw more of Audrey than almost anybody else during that period, although I was basically left on my own, I saw very little of anybody else.  Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
You also mention Valdo Pons.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Valdo Pons, yes, who was one of the lecturers.  There was also Ronnie Frankenberg, who\rquote s not mentioned. He was there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Oh yes.  Well, 
you do mention him, actually, but not at the beginning.  What you actually say is that Frankenberg was very simplistic in saying that if you can\rquote 
t participate with the knowledge and approval of the people to be studied, you should not be there at all, so you do mention Frankenberg!  (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 I do mention him!

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
But what was your feeling about him at the time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 We didn\rquote 
t get on terribly well.  I got on much better with Valdo.  But actually, my relationship with them was so limited - I was amazed that I was just kind of left.  I was told I could go into seminars, and occasionally I\rquote d go in, and they\rquote d say, 
\'93How is it?\'94  But there was never any kind of systematic discussion of where I was up to and what I was doing.  I mean, it was slightly 
bizarre.  But it may have been the anthropological tradition that you leave people for long periods in fieldwork. I think, at the time, I probably thought I was being neglected, but as I look back with a little more wisdom, I think it may have been that t
hat they thought that\rquote s what anthropologists do \endash 
 you just leave people in the field and let them of swish around for a while!  But by the time that came, I was out, you see, because this job had come up.  So it might have been very different if I\rquote d spent a longer period in the field.
\par 
