\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Not a lot, because to get close to Max, you had to be a fanatical supporter of Manchester United, and I was not!  (LAUGHS)  That was the way it was!  But I always thought Max was interesting.  I mean, he was
 an incredibly egocentric dominant figure.  He was a very big man, and they used to have seminars, and if Max was present, everybody waited to see what Max would say.  Max always dominated everything.  He was the one to speak first, and he would change di
rection, he would determine the way. If the seminar was being well-presented, if Max liked it, it went well.  If Max didn\rquote t like what he heard, it didn\rquote t go well.  When Max wasn\rquote 
t there, it was a quite different kettle of fish.  But, of course, he was a very smart guy, and I\rquote d read all his basic books, being in his Department. But I didn\rquote t learn anything kind of directly, it didn\rquote t connect to my work.  I don
\rquote t think he was terribly interested in my work, I think he was very much an African anthropologist, he
 did know a lot about Africa and a lot of the people he worked most closely with had been doing fieldwork in Africa, and, of course, were involved in African politics.  A lot of people they\rquote 
d worked with, like Kenneth Kaunda, they were all on first name terms with people like Kaunda \endash  so there was a whole kind of African network which, obviously, I wasn\rquote 
t part of.  I was very much on the periphery of that.  It changed when Peter came.
