ays.  We got on quite well, but he was always a Marxist, looking to convert everyone to Marxism, and so it got up my nose a bit.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes, you mentioned, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5836233 earlier, about a great deal of \lquote talking politics\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 , but you didn\rquote t exactly explain what your view was!  Is it possible to say any more on that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
What, on my political views? Well, the only thing to say is I\rquote m not a - I\rquote ve never been a joiner. I have no sense of loyalty to a group, and I\rquote m deeply suspicious of any group which would want to command my loyalty \endash 
 very reluctant to do that.  So in that sense I\rquote ve probably voted for all the main Parties at different times.  Much later when I went to become Chief Inspector in London, people automatically assumed I was a 
member of the Labour Party, which I wasn\rquote t, and didn\rquote t want to be. My politics have swung around - I suppose broadly centre, and more often left of centre than right of centre, but I\rquote 
ve not been a joiner.  I loved politics, I loved the cut and thrust, I lo
ved working in London, I loved my time when I was a Policy Advisor to Estelle Morris, and when I knew Charles Clarke, and I knew three Secretaries of State in Education very well, and I loved being close up to politics, but I was never truly part of it.  
And every time people have said, \'93Will you be an advisor to us on this, that and the other?\'94 and they say, \'93Are you a member?\'94  I have to say, \'93Well, no, I\rquote m not.  And I\rquote ve no intention of ever being\'94
.  So I think politics is endlessly fascinating, but for me, as an observer rather than a participant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 One of my teac}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5836233 her friends described you as a \lquote radical\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
.  Is that, to you, a compliment?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Oh well, I\rquote 
ve been a radical in education terms, yes.  Oh, unquestionably, yes.  But a radical in the sense that I\rquote ve challenged the status quo, so if you said was I broadly sympathetic to the comprehensive move \endash 
 yes.  Am I one of these fighting upholders of the comprehensive principle?  No.  Because, actually, that isn\rquote t the way education works.  The people haven\rquote t come up with a neat - every time they come up with a neat answer, it\rquote 
s flawed.  So in that sense I\rquote m a radical, in the sense of trying to go to the root of things.  But I could easily go with a Conservative Party on some issue if I thought it was the right thing educationally.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Okay.  I just wanted to go back to one point about the book, which I find very interesting, which is the way you talk about using the boys\rquote  own words, which was possible, because you\rquote d done this tape-recording.  Would yo
u like to say any more about why do that?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13701623 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Well, for me, it was about the quality of the evidence base.  Most of the stuff I was reading in the Anthropology Department didn\rquote 
t actually quote anybody.  You described what people did, and so on, and people would say, \'93Somebody was an informant\'94
, but you would very rarely see a chunk of text.  But to me, my saying somebody had said something to me is not the same as quoting the precise words that I could actually document.  Now, it\rquote s true that those documents have gone, and it\rquote 
s a pity in a way.  It\rquote s a pity that, at the time, it would have taken too long to transcribe this endless stuff, but even the stuff I did partially transcribe I wish had been retained because there was lots of stuff, of course, I ne
ver used.  As always you discard 90 per cent or more.  But to me, I didn\rquote t think the thing would be authentic, so I wanted two things the Department didn\rquote t want me to do \endash  they didn\rquote 
t want me to have lots of statistics, and they didn\rquote t want lots of quotes, but I regarde}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13701623 d both as crucial to my story.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 There were bits in the middle that would have read \endash 
 bits about Clint and his gang - that would have read probably more like a conventional piece of anthropology, so I tried to do some bits that were a bit like
 what they were doing.  But in the end, I felt I had to carve my own way.  But it was done [with] almost a naivety, rather than a kind of complete self-confidence that I had a way of doing it.  It was much more intuitive that, somehow, the bits of my expe
rience said, \'93Document this as best you can in these circumstances, and if you have to use multiple methods\'94 \endash  a term I would hardly have recognised, I suppose \endash  I would have said, \'93Yes, that\rquote s fine!\'94
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13331801 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But it\rquote 
