no!  I was completing the work.  The Report was being drafted at a late stage, and the Chief Inspector\rquote s job came up, and the Chief Education Officer took me out for lunch and he said, \'93How\rquote s the Committee going?\'94  I said, \'93Well, we
\rquote re very close to the end.  It\rquote s very good.  We\rquote re getting it all together\'94, I thought it was just a kind of general chat.  And then he said to me, \'93Have you anyone you\rquote d recommend for the Chief Inspector\rquote s post?
\'94  And I said, \'93Well, I can\rquote t think of anybody.  I don\rquote t really know that kind of person terribly well\'94.  And he said, \'93Would you be interested?\'94
  Well, I was completely shaken!  It never would have crossed my mind in a thousand years!  And he said, \'93Well, you realise you\rquote d be in a position to help to implement your own Report\'94.  So I went home, and I thought, \'93I\rquote 
ve got a quiet little niche in Oxford, where I love my College dearly, and I\rquote m pretty happy, but this is one of those things that comes along once in a lifetime\'94.  The Fellows of my College said I was very courageo
us, which meant, of course, they thought I was completely idiotic (LAUGHS) in showing an interest!  Anyway, they appointed me, and off I went!  And I\rquote m very glad I did.
