\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yeah. Yes, open-ended, and they would fill it in.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 They didn\rquote 
t mind doing that, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 No.  Whenever you
\rquote re hanging around \endash  there\rquote s quite a lot of hanging around in hospitals, when juniors have nothing particular to do, the hours are long \endash  but nobody seemed to mind being interviewed. It wasn\rquote 
t always easy to get them to agree to my going in the first place, some specialties refused, but the orthopods were very very good, and I just went to orthopaedics in several hospit
als.  And then the question was, what were we going to do?  Well, of course, we\rquote re being paid to improve the training.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Can you explain how you got the funding?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, the funding was given by the post-graduate Dean.  He just forked out a great pile of money!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
It must have been quite a lot, if there was a whole team of you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yes.  It was a pile of money!  I mean, the medics tend not to be terribly short.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
And you had money to transcribe your recordings?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yeah, we appoi
nted a full-time secretary who spent most of the time transcribing.  And the question was, then, how were we going to justify the money?  So I suppose three things happened.  One was we produced a training pack for the people in each hospital who are resp
onsible for training. There\rquote s a person called the Clinical Tutor, who was a consultant in any field, who accepts a kind of responsibility for the overall training - though in detail, of course, it\rquote 
s left to the consultant with whom the junior happens to be working - but they\rquote 
re supposed to lay on some kind of training, so we prepared quite a complex pack of materials.  It was clear that the key method of improving teaching was to improve the questioning: some were very good, and some were utterly hopeless at
 questioning their juniors.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
What does the hopeless person do, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, they simply wouldn\rquote t ask any questions, or they\rquote d ask a few closed questions.  They wouldn\rquote t ask questions that required them to think.  They\rquote d point to something and say, \'93Which nerve is that?\'94
, in the operation, or, \'93Where would you cut?\'94 and so on.  They didn\rquote t ask really powerful questions.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
What would be an example of a powerful question?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, a powerful question would require them to do cognitive work, so they would say, \'93What are the options at this point?\'94  And then the junior has to think very hard about what the options are, because they\rquote 
ve all got to be reasonable options, and if it\rquote s a good question, it\rquote ll be a point where there\rquote 
s probably one particularly favourable option, but there are other things that could be done under certain circumstances.  So what we did was produce books on the training of juniors, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 On the Job Training}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859  we called it, and produced two books \endash  on
e for surgeons and one for physicians - because it became clear that physicians are very very different. The apprenticeship mode is particularly strong with surgeons, less strong with physicians.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Why do you think that might be?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 I think because there
\rquote s much more physical - you\rquote re doing things with your hands, as a surgeon, inevitably, whereas a physician, they\rquote 
re rarely doing a great deal with their hands. Just in some areas, but the skills are mainly diagnostic and then prescribing. So the on
e I worked with, which was dermatology, the art there is diagnosis.  Treatments are really quite difficult.  The skill is getting the right diagnosis.  A lot of skin conditions just look terrible, but it\rquote s not terribly clear what\rquote 
s causing it.  So then the question becomes - the training tends to be not a physical skill, it\rquote 
s simply looking and building up a knowledge base to be able to recognise symptoms, and then to decide which of the many kind of drugs and treatments and creams and so on is likely to work.  So it\rquote 
s a much more intellectual activity, being a physician.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Dermatology is just one kind of physician.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yes.  Because I always think of physicians as having a wider view, medically, than many other specialties.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 That\rquote 
s true only in two cases where we looked at physicians.  One was care of the elderly, or geriatrics, which is a much looked down upon area, because there\rquote 
s not much money in it for private practice. Whereas, I tell you, there is in dermatology, because GP
s are hopeless at dermatology, so a lot of people go and see a consultant privately.  And at the time there was about a year long waiting list to see a consultant dermatologist.  There\rquote s a lot of money in it!  Care for the elderly, no, there
\rquote s no money, because people dump their old folk, or they don\rquote t have any folk to be dumped by \endash  they end up in a hospital.  And it\rquote s a complicated area, because most old people, if they\rquote 
re ill, are suffering from multiple conditions, so they have to be very good, as physicians, to cover a wide range.  But apart from that, and parts of paediatrics, most physicians are highly specialised.  They\rquote 
re going to be neurologists, or rheumatologists, they\rquote re pretty specialised.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 And I\rquote 
m not entirely clear, you just looked at dermatologists for, or did you do more ethnography with other kinds the physicians?
\par  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Oh no, I did ethnography with all of the people I looked at, and I persuaded most of my colleagues - some were wanted to do little surveys, but I think the majority
 of the team did what I wanted, which was really to triangulate across through questionnaires, interviews, and then observation, and gathered material in this way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Well, I was only able to read the surgeons\rquote  book, because I couldn\rquote t find the physicians through the British Library Catalogue.  But, one thing I wanted to ask you is, you co-author it with two \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yes.  Two doctors, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Who were they?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15560342 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 They were two junior doctors, and other people were doing other kinds of writing.  I mean, almost all the surgery was left to me.  The physicians
\rquote  book, it was written with some colleagues from my Department.  But nobody wanted to do surgery except me!  So I thought I\rquote d better recruit two doctors.  They were registrars, but they were fairly well up the scale \endash 
 of course, both became consultants a little bit later \endash and they didn\rquote t really collect the material, but the examples I wanted to use had to be telling examples that would work, so I needed their view.  And it seemed to me reasonable 
\endash  I mean I was at the end of my career, I didn\rquote t have to worry, so I said, \'93Be the joint author\'94, which they were thrilled by, you know, because it would add to their CVs. 
So they went through the material with me, and occasionally found me better examples than the ones that I\rquote d collected.  I also felt that having some real doctors as co-authors, might legitimate the book.  I don\rquote t k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2847790 now whether it did or it didn\rquote t!  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But, of course, I\rquote 
d not written any piece of actual ethnography, and I thought \endash  although I was busy at the time, because I was Head of Department and doing a lot of things \endash  I thought, \'93I must do an ethnographic piece\'94
.  So I wrote a piece on the cardio-thoracic people I worked with in Papworth.  Papworth is an interesting hospital, because it specialises in cardio-thoracic surgery, but it\rquote s interesting because it\rquote 
s a hospital outside Cambridge, which is an ex-TB hospital, and still has the isolation [wards]. Outs
ide the wards there are balconies where they used to wrap up TB patients and push them out at night, they used to sleep in the open air in the old days.  And because it\rquote 
s a tiny little hospital on its own, it developed a very distinctive kind of culture, and I felt very very comfortable there.  I enjoyed going there.  I also didn\rquote 
t have to face going through the traffic to other hospitals in the region, because my home was reasonably close.  So I used to pop in there quit}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15560342 
e a lot for training sessions.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But 
I then discovered- I was interviewing some juniors first, and I interviewed two juniors there, and they both gave me such a complimentary statement about the quality of their training - which was slightly unusual because the juniors were often very critic
al, the training they weren\rquote t getting \endash  and they said it was terrific there.  So I went to see one of the consultants and said, \'93Could I come?\'94  And he said, \'93Of course.  Of course\'94
.  So I spent quite a lot of time there.  The surgery, of course, was partic
ularly interesting anyway, and I was able to meet some anaesthetists because the Clinical Tutor there was an anaesthetist, so I got a bit of time with them. And because they were giving much better training than average, particularly meeting and discussin
g cases either in the clinics or privately looking at X-rays, I decided to write it up, and so I wrote an article that was based almost entirely on what I\rquote 
d observed.  And you remember I said, last time, when I did my Lumley Study, I thought of publishing it, I thought, \'93Well, go to the top\'94, so I went to the Routledge Kegan and Paul International Series.  In this case, I wrote it up, and I thought, 
\'93Well, do it again.  Go to the top!\'94  So I wrote to the editor of the BMA!  (LAUGHS)  And he wrote back an interesting letter, he said, \'93We never publish things like this, we only publish things, really, by medics\'94, he said, \'93but it\rquote 
s such an intriguing piece\'94, he said, \'93I\rquote m going to publish it!\'94  Which he did!  I can\rquote t remember what year it is.  I\rquote ve got a copy of it somewhere, I\rquote ll try and fish it out.
