d kind of come full circle at that point.  I\rquote d got, in the late stage of my career, I\rquote d got another little bit of ethnography there, packed away!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Do you think that the people who commissioned you in the first place were surprised you wanted to talk to the junior doctors as well as the consultants?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yes, I think they were.  I think they were very pleased actually, because it implied we weren\rquote t going to pop in and - well, I think, at first, they thought we\rquote d go along and then, because we\rquote d co
me from a Faculty of Education, we were going to tell them how to teach. It was obvious to me that would have been a terrible mistake, especially since so much of it was on the job training, and we weren\rquote 
t particularly expert in on the job training anyway.
  We were much more used to a kind of formal teaching and learning, but there was very little of that, and whatever was done for juniors, of that kind, was not done by consultants, it would be done by the Royal Colleges.  They\rquote 
d go off on a course, and be taught formally.  And while they\rquote re studying for the FRCS or whatever it was they were doing \endash  it was the FRCS at that time \endash 
 much of their work was studying stuff at home, and just kind of memorising the wretched stuff.  But the practical stuff is what ma
kes a surgeon, obviously, and there was no way we had insight into that that could be separated from observing their daily practice.  So, as I think you\rquote ll see in the book, we\rquote 
re trying to make much more of the ward rounds.  Very little was made of ward rounds.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 That\rquote 
s for teaching purposes, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yes.  Far too little by most consultants.  And so we had this idea that at the end of the ward round, if they would let the juniors ask qu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15560342 estions \endash 
 and we called it the \lquote Three minute round up\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859  - 
we were trying to find ways that you could insert small amounts of time that were dedicated to the juniors being given some genuine legitimate space.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
