Two reasons, mainly, for coming out.  Well, perhaps three.  One, some promises were made when I went, that weren\rquote t fulfilled. But the two more important ones were I wasn\rquote 
t really getting along with the Chairman. Only later did I realise that, having read something by Sir Adrian Cadbury \endash  a very clever book \endash  which says, \'93
The art of running one of these organisations, or a business firm, is getting the right chemistry between the Chairman of the Board and the Chief Executive of a company.  This is a crucial relationship of high degree of trust and compatibility\'94. And
 that wasn\rquote t working.  And the third reason was, I began to see that, despite being a Labour government, their views on the assessment regime that had been introduced by the Conservatives - they were stuck with it, and they weren\rquote 
t going to modify it. So I thought, \'93I\rquote m going to be here for another three years, and nothing will have changed.  They aren\rquote t going to change anything\'94.  
