\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8334801 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Oh, I think it needed an overhaul. I mean, we were examining far too much.  There was too much going on, there were too many tests.  The tests were too narrow.  The tests were unreliable.  They were very low in validity and reliability, and we were puttin
g so much stress on them.  Parents were being told that these key stage tests were crucial.  And kids were getting labelled with the number that they\rquote 
d got.  And the evidence was that for those levels, post levels, they were only correct +1 or -1,  that was quite a lot of \endash  and kids were getting labelled with these [tests]. So I felt it wasn\rquote 
t really working, and we needed to make changes.  I also thought the curriculum was getting too jammed up. It had already been massively over-prescriptive, and the reforms were still reducing teacher creativity.  So, I tried to make pushes i}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8334801 n the direction I wanted to go.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But you\rquote 
ve got to be very careful when you\rquote re a head of that kind of organisation, because you\rquote re not supposed to speak explicitly against government policy, you\rquote ve to do it in a kind of slightly coded way \endash 
 which I did from time to time, so I didn\rquote t get into trouble with Ministers, on the contrary, I got on very well with them!  And particularly when Estelle Morris became Secretary of State \endash  who I got along with very very well}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8334801  indeed.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 But I thought, \'93The time is to go\'94.  I\rquote 
m not going to waste three or four more years doing something that I\rquote m not getting all that much out of, and I think is not going to leave anything behind.  I was just becoming an administrator, allowing the syste}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8334801 m to tick over perfectly well.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
As it happened, when I left, the Chairman took over and then there was a major disaster and he was fired!  But that\rquote s the way life goes!  And, in fact, my successor was fired in the end too \endash  a man they brought in from Australia.  They
\rquote re difficult jobs, and I had to say to Estelle Morris when she was Secretary of State, I had to say, \'93It\rquote s only a matter of time before something seriously goes wrong, because we\rquote ve got millions of [exam] scripts 
going round the country.  The system is so overloaded, something is bound to go wrong one of these days\'94
.  And there were several mini crises while I was there, which we managed to head off, because you knew there was going to be a major public scandal, and the Ministers would find it very difficult, so it was that sense of you\rquote 
re just hanging on desperately, and keeping your fingers crossed all the time, despite every effort, because you simply can\rquote t control a thing of that size.  You\rquote ve got to remember, when we were at [primary] school, there were no big exams 
\endash  you had \lquote O\rquote  Level, GCSE and \lquote A\rquote  Level \endash  but now, it goes right through the primary school, and many kids were going from the age of 9, doing some kind of examination every year, until they\rquote re 18 \endash  
so the whole system was absolutely massive.  And, of course, eventually the key stage 3 tests were dropped, because the firm that was handling it made a bodge up, and then the Secretary of State was forced to abolish the whole thing because it was so comp
licated.  
