\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13722979 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes, lots of experience, anyway!  So I think there\rquote s a kind of continuity there.  But I don\rquote 
t think anybody would ever read my work from beginning to end, because you wouldn\rquote t have that kind of range of interest.  When I meet people who know my work, they nearly always pick out one or two bits that\rquote s hit them for some reas
on, and they don\rquote t know the rest.   The rest is kind of hidden.  So I could meet two people who are kind enough to think well of something I\rquote ve done, but they would have nothing in common, they wouldn\rquote 
t have read anything in common, because they\rquote ve come into the work at different points in my life when my interests were very different.  So I\rquote m not sure what I\rquote m proud of, I just think I\rquote 
ve been exceptionally fortunate that people have asked me to do things, or given me opportunities which were really terrific ones, and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13722979 
 they were right at that time.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 It allowed me to just go and do something slightly different, whereas I think most of the academic colleagues I
\rquote ve got, and still have as friends, have often pursued a much straighter line. They\rquote ve developed a lin
e of work and become terrifically expert in that line of work, which is actually the kind of thing that Cambridge really approves of.  They want somebody who\rquote s an expert on the Third Crusade, and they\rquote 
ve been studying the Third Crusade for 50 years, and they are }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid461552 the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 world authority on the Third Crusade!  Now, I would have found that very hard.  But I think social scientists are perhaps made of different stuff.  I mean the social scientists I
\rquote ve really admired, the Erving Goffmans, or the Alvin Gouldners, what\rquote 
s striking about the really great figures - or Robert Merton perhaps, perhaps Merton most of all - is their ability to move from one area to another.  Merton wonderfully moved fields, and
 then started whole new things up.  So I think the social sciences have that, and, in a sense, obviously at a very very much lower level, I\rquote 
ve wanted to do that kind of thing, which is to move from one thing to something slightly different, and can do it.  But I may just be saying, \'93Well, I\rquote m a natural social scientist\'94, as opposed to, say, historian \endash 
 who you will understand \endash  often does have this kind of much more linear approach to their career and their expertise.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13331801 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 Yes.  I think there
\rquote s another th
ing that runs through your work, to my mind, which might be related to your interest in ethnography, actually, but this instinct to build from where you are, rather than to get the great interpretations or structures from outside and impose them. You are 
always suggesting the solution seems to be build from where you are, what you know already.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 
Yes.  I think that is true.  What I\rquote ve tried to do, particularly in the more recent years, I\rquote ve tried to find something outside that I can import to throw a light on where you are, starting from there.  So sometimes my friends say to me, 
\'93Why were you reading in that area?  It\rquote s nothing to do with this\'94.  And I would say, \'93No, it isn\rquote t anything to do with it, but I read, often, out of curiosity, and I see a connection with something, and I think, \lquote 
Can you forge a connection?  Can you use this from the outside, to throw light on something inside?\rquote \'94  And I\rquote ve enjoyed doing that.  I think, sometimes, I\rquote m only partially successful, to be honest!  I think, sometimes
, people in education think, \'93Why is he bringing all this weird stuff in that he found somewhere?\'94  But I don\rquote t know, picking something - well, I won\rquote t give an example, but often I\rquote 
ve been reading something, or thinking about something, and I see a connection and try and bring it in, but it\rquote s not to try and force where we are, the phenomena that I\rquote m dealing with, it\rquote 
s not trying to force them into a different shape, it\rquote s merely trying to illuminate them from a different angle.  But I I think I learnt that from the great social scientists, didn\rquote t I?  This is what they\rquote ve been good at \endash 
 that you shine a slightly different light on the world and it looks a bit different.  And in my own field \endash  you\rquote ve got to remember, most of the people I\rquote ve worked with are not social scientists, they\rquote 
re just working in education, and they live in that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid461552 narrow world of what they call \lquote education\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 , and when they all feed off one another, and I think, as a social scientist, you\rquote re always wanting to say, \'93Yes, respect the phenomena that you\rquote re dealing with\'94 
\endash  a good ethnographer always respects phenomena \endash  \'93but you\rquote ve got to shine a slightly different light on it if you really want to understand what it is, otherwise you won\rquote t understand it fully, you\rquote 
ll simply go on taking it for granted, and assuming you know it when you don\rquote t\'94.  These other lights allow you to question and reconceptualise.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 And one last one 
\endash  you might want to skip this one, actually!  (LAUGHS)  But looking at your life as a whole now, what do you think has been the worst and the best thing about it?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid461552 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13331801\charrsid13331801 David:\tab }{
