s the most incredible luck.  I mean, it\rquote s kept repeatin}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid461552 g itself.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9443859\charrsid9443859 The worst thing about my life?  I find that very hard to say, because, I mean \'85 I\rquote m an atheist, but if religion were 
true, and suddenly the Good Lord called me to his presence, and said, \'93Hargreaves, what complaints have you got?\'94  I\rquote d have to say, \'93Well, to be honest, God, I don\rquote t have any!\'94  And I don\rquote 
t.  I mean, any grumbles, or the worst things, would be relatively trivial.  I\rquote m very conscious, as I imagine you are, when you get to a certain age, you\rquote re very conscious that, at certain points, you made a decision, and it\rquote 
s changed the whole direction of your life - there are all these binary choices you make, and the worst thing I sometimes think - some of my closer friends say, \'93You\rquote d have been a very good barrister\'94, because I love a good argument, and I
\rquote ll persist. [But] would my life have been fuller if I\rquote d become a lawyer instead, if I\rquote d read law and not psychology
 at Cambridge, how would my life have been different?  Or would I have been as miserable as sin, as a lawyer, or would it have just been a whole other set of doors would have opened?\'94  So it\rquote s an odd way of saying, \'93What\rquote 
s the worst thing in my life\'94, it was having to make choices that ruled out other possibilities, because there are times when I think, \'93Oh, I could have done that!\'94  \'93Wouldn\rquote t that have been interesting!\'94  But you can\rquote 
t have it all, and you\rquote re stuck with the binary choices you make \endash  you either go that way, or you don\rquote t.
